> Apple and maple syrup may sound like ingredients for a breakfast or a baking recipe, 
> but we've managed to work those flavors into a quick and simple pork dish. 
> The maple syrup gets stirred into the sauce, coating each cutlet in sticky deliciousness. 
> The apple, on the other hand, gives a fruity boost to the creamy side salad. 
> And with hearty couscous to back up all those flavors, you've got nothing less than 
> sweet, sweet perfection.

== Couscous ==

Wash and dry all produce. Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}, separating whites from 
greens. Pick @rosemary{1/4%ounce} leaves from stems; finely chop leaves until you have 
@?rosemary leaves{1%tsp}.

Halve, core, and dice @apple{1}.

Heat a drizzle of @olive oil{1%teaspoon} in a #small pot{} over medium-high heat. Add 
scallion whites and half the chopped rosemary. Cook until fragrant, ~{30%seconds} to 
~{1%minute}.

Pour in @water{3/4%cup}. Bring to a boil and immediately stir in @couscous{1/2%cup} and 
a large pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}. Turn off heat, cover, and let stand until 
tender, ~{8-10%minutes}.

== Pork Cutlets ==

Meanwhile, pat @pork cutlets{12%ounce} dry with #paper towels{}; season all over with 
salt and pepper. Melt @butter{1%tablespoon} in a #large pan{} over high heat. Add 
pork and cook until browned and cooked through, ~{2-3%minutes} per side. (For 4, you 
may need to cook in batches.) Transfer to a #plate{}.

== Glaze ==

Heat same pan over medium heat. Add remaining chopped rosemary, @white wine vinegar{1%tablespoon}, 
@maple syrup{2%tablespoon}, @chicken stock concentrate{1}, and @water{1/4%cup}. Simmer 
until slightly thickened, ~{1-2%minutes}. Stir in @butter{1%tablespoon}, then season with 
salt and pepper. Return pork to pan, turning to coat in glaze. Turn off heat.

== Apple Salad ==

In a #medium bowl{}, whisk together @mayonnaise{2%tablespoon} and remaining 
@white wine vinegar{1%tablespoon}. Add @mixed greens{2%ounce} and apple; toss to combine. 
Season with salt and pepper.

== To Serve ==

Fluff couscous with a #fork{} and divide between plates. Top with pork. Drizzle with any 
remaining glaze. Garnish with scallion greens. Serve with salad on the side.